Sarcasm Detection¶

Acknowledgement

Misra, Rishabh, and Prahal Arora. "Sarcasm Detection using Hybrid Neural Network." arXiv preprint arXiv:1908.07414 (2019).

Required Files given in below link.

https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1xUnF35naPGU63xwRDVGc-DkZ3M8V5mMk

Problem Description:¶

  • Past studies in Sarcasm Detection mostly make use of Twitter datasets collected using hashtag based supervision but such datasets are noisy in terms of labels and language. Furthermore, many tweets are replies to other tweets and detecting sarcasm in these requires the availability of contextual tweets.

  • In this hands-on project, the goal is to build a model to detect whether a sentence is sarcastic or not, using Bidirectional LSTMs.

Data Description:¶

  • News Headlines dataset for Sarcasm Detection. The dataset is collected from two news websites, theonion.com and huffingtonpost.com. This new dataset has the following advantages over the existing Twitter datasets:
  • Since news headlines are written by professionals in a formal manner, there are no spelling mistakes and informal usage. This reduces the sparsity and also increases the chance of finding pre-trained embedding.
  • Furthermore, since the sole purpose of TheOnion is to publish sarcastic news, we get high-quality labels with much less noise as compared to Twitter datasets. Unlike tweets that reply to other tweets, the news headlines obtained are selfcontained. This would help us in teasing apart the real sarcastic elements

Content¶

  • Each record consists of three attributes:
  • is_sarcastic: 1 if the record is sarcastic otherwise 0
  • headline: the headline of the news article
  • article_link: link to the original news article. Useful in collecting supplementary data

Reference¶

https://github.com/rishabhmisra/News-Headlines-Dataset-For-Sarcasm-Detection

Get the Word Embeddings using Embedding file as given below.¶

In [0]:
EMBEDDING_FILE = './glove.6B.200d.txt' #glove embedding file

embeddings = {} #empty dict
for o in open(EMBEDDING_FILE):
    word = o.split(" ")[0] #split
    # print(word)
    embd = o.split(" ")[1:] #split
    embd = np.asarray(embd, dtype='float32') 
    # print(embd)
    embeddings[word] = embd

Create a weight matrix for words in training docs¶

  • Creating weight matrix
In [22]:
embedding_matrix = np.zeros((num_words, 200)) #zero matrix

for word, i in tokenizer.word_index.items(): #for loop
    embedding_vector = embeddings.get(word) #embedding vector 
    if embedding_vector is not None:
        embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector

len(embeddings.values()) #length of embedding values
Out[22]:
400000

Create and Compile your Model ( 7 marks)¶

  • Creating Sequential model instance and then Embedding layer, Bidirectional(LSTM) layer, then dense and dropout layers.
  • Adding a Flatten() layer before Final fully connected layer to get a single value as output from the network.
  • A final dense layer with sigmoid activation for binary classification.
In [23]:
model = Sequential() #sequential model
model.add(Input(shape=(maxlen,)))
model.add(Embedding(num_words, embedding_size, weights = [embedding_matrix])) #Embedding layer
model.add(Bidirectional(LSTM(128, return_sequences = True, recurrent_dropout=0.1))) #Bi-directional LSTM layer with 128 units
model.add(Dropout(0.1)) #Dropout layer
model.add(Dense(128,activation='relu')) #Dense layer with relu activation
model.add(Dropout(0.1)) #Dropout layer
model.add(Dense(64,activation='relu')) #Dense layer with relu activation
model.add(Dropout(0.1)) #Dropout layer
model.add(Dense(32,activation='relu')) #Dense layer with relu activation
model.add(Dropout(0.1)) #Dropout layer
model.add(Dense(16,activation='relu')) #Dense layer with relu activation
model.add(Dropout(0.2)) #Dropout layer
model.add(Flatten()) #Flatten layer
model.add(Dense(1,activation='sigmoid')) #Dense layer with sigmoid activation
model.compile(optimizer='adam',loss='binary_crossentropy',metrics=['accuracy']) #Compile
model.summary() #Summary

ax.plot(np.sqrt(model_H.history['val_accuracy']), 'r' ,label='val') #Plot validation accuracy
ax.set_xlabel(r'Epoch', fontsize=14) #set xlabel
ax.set_ylabel(r'Accuracy', fontsize=14) #set ylabel
ax.legend() #set legend
ax.tick_params(labelsize=20) #set label size
  • The Training accuracy is higher than validation because the network is slightly overfitting. While, Training loss has decreased per epoch the validation loss has been constant.

Sample Predictions:¶

  • Below are sample predictions generated from the network for sample headlines which are not present in the dataset.
In [26]:
headline = ['How a simple breathing trick can change your life'] #Sample Headline
headline = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(headline) #Tokenize
headline = pad_sequences(headline, maxlen=maxlen, dtype='int32', value=0) #pad_sequence

sarcasm = model.predict(headline,batch_size=1,verbose = 2) #Predict
sarcasm1 = np.round(sarcasm) #Round predictions
if(sarcasm1 == 0): #check if non-sarcastic
    print("The headline is Not-sarcastic.")
elif (sarcasm1 == 1): #check if sarcastic
    print("The headline is sarcastic.")
